article.headline: Stokes saves cold-shooting Cincy in opener

images.name: Huggins Bob 021123 vert top
images.caption: After watching his Bearcats go scoreless for nine minutes, Bob Huggins couldn't stay seated in the second half.

article.linkText: Cold-shooting Cincy struggles to get past Tennessee Tech
article.story:
CINCINNATI (AP) -- No. 20 Cincinnati (No. 23 AP) went more than nine minutes without scoring, but Leonard Stokes ended the drought with 15 consecutive points as the Bearcats rallied for a 54-48 victory Saturday over Tennessee Tech.

Cincinnati (1-0) missed 15 consecutive shots and fell behind by
six points midway through the second half, before Stokes asserted
himself. The senior guard drove to the basket, took jumpers off a
spin move and finished with a team-high 21.

<photo1>

	   Coach Bob Huggins, who had a massive heart attack eight weeks
ago, came out dressed in a black suit, black pants and fuchsia
shirt and kept his temper in check until the Bearcats went cold.

	   Then, he railed at the referees and his out-of-sync offense as
well. Stokes got him calmed down with his personal scoring spurt,
and Taron Barker hit a rare 3-pointer and a pair of free throws
that built the lead to 49-43 with 59 seconds left.

	   Jason Harrell missed a pair of bank shots from directly
underneath the basket with 24 seconds left, scuttling the Golden
Eagles' last chance to catch up. Cameron Crisp led Tennessee Tech
with 16 points.

	   Cincinnati shot only 27.9 percent from the field, but its
trademark man-to-man defense contained Tennessee Tech's
high-percentage shooters and forced 17 turnovers.

	   Playing its opener under new head coach Mike Sutton, Tennessee
Tech also bogged down on offense, setting up a back-and-forth game.
There were eight lead changes, and neither team led by more than
eight points.

	   Unable to get the ball inside, the Bearcats fired away from the
perimeter and made few. They were only 4-of-22 on 3-point attempts.

	   The Golden Eagles are coming off their best season -- 27-7 and
the Ohio Valley Conference title -- and were looking to add to their
recent history of season-opening surprises.

	   Tennessee Tech won at South Carolina 73-67 to open the 2000
season, and lost 72-63 at Tennessee in last season's opener.

	   The Golden Eagles stayed with the bulkier Bearcats through a
first half that featured lousy shooting by Cincinnati's top two
players, Stokes (1-for-8) and Jason Maxiell (1-7).

	   Barker had a steal and layup and a jumper during an eight-point
run that helped Cincinnati hold a 27-23 halftime lead.

	   Huggins kicked the scorer's table during Cincinnati's first
exhibition and got a technical in the second one, but was more
low-key Saturday night. He paced on the sideline but didn't even
remove his jacket -- his usual indication of displeasure -- as
Tennessee Tech pulled ahead in the second half.

	   Five players scored during a 12-point run that put Tennessee
Tech ahead 35-29 midway through the second half, its biggest lead
of the game. That's when Huggins started screaming and Stokes
started scoring.

	   The senior guard hit four consecutive shots, ranging from a
driving bank shot to a jumper off a spin move, to lead the
comeback.
